included.description:
This course introduced students to the concepts and practices of engineering human-centered interactive systems and environments using low-cost micro-controllers. 

I used tools such as Arduinos and Processing to construct prototypes using electronic components including buttons, switches, low-cost sensors, displays, LEDs, motors, and wireless communication modules.

In my final project, I designed and fabricated a physical prototype of a more secure mailbox using NFC technology, pressure sensors, solenoid locks, LEDs, LCD screens, and C+ coding. The purpose was to tackle the problem of identity theft in modern mailboxes.
included.title: Physical Computing & Prototyping - Secure Snail Mail

included.description:
Quarter long project for HCDE 417 (Usability Research Techniques)

The project for this quarter was to run a usability study on a local civic engagement websites or mobile applications. In a group of four we decided to work on the LivingVoter'sGuide website, which is was developed as an online tool to inform voting decisions, inspire public trust in one another, and reclaim citizensâ power and shared responsibility for making our democracy work.  

The major steps to prepare to run the usability was to first develop a usability test plan, then create a usability test kit for the test itself. Within the usability test plan we established our project goals, target user population, key tasks, and key usability questions.

For the usability test kit we prepared the following: participant screener, consent form, pre-test questionnaire, facilitation script, note-taking forms, post-task questionnaire, post-test questionnaire, and debriefing interview questions.

For the actual usability study we first ran a pilot test to work out any problems we may have initially overseen. After running the pilot test we were able to reflect and adjust for the future usability studies. In total we conducted 4 usability studies and between all of our members we rotated roles as tech manager, project manager, facilitator, and note taker.

To conclude this project analyzed the results of our usability study and provided suggestions on improvements of the site. We compiled all of our findings and analysis into a final report whose audience was meant to be the client.
included.title: Usability Testing - Washington's Living Voter's Guide

included.description:
Quarter long project for HCDE 455 (User Interface Design). 

The project for this quarter was to follow the design process and create a user interface that was intuitive, effective, efficient, likable, and affordable. The topic we were given was to develop a user interface for a Celestial Navigation Simulator. The topic itself was a curveball and as a team we figured it out and learned a lot about the design process along the way.

The major steps to the project were the following: Prospectus, Background Review, Persona, Storyboard, Task Analysis, Flipbook, Flipbook - Field Trial, Prototype, Prototype - Field Trial, Presentation, Final Report. 

Since we had such a complex topic, communication was key and we worked well as a group to get everyone informed on what was being done for the week.
included.title: User Interface Design - Celestial Navigation Training System
